## 2. Your Role (from the Team Plan)

You are the **RAG Baseline + Evaluation Lead**. Your deliverables:

1. **RAG baseline spec + integration** — define baseline retrieval (BM25 first), ensure gatherer produces ranked file paths compatible with evaluation
2. **Evaluation output** — Recall@K for K=5/10/20 over files, produce first results table
3. **Two cheap ablations** — BM25 vs Dense OR BM25 vs Hybrid, plus K sensitivity
4. **Write-up contribution** — methods paragraph (retrieval + Recall@K definition), early results paragraph + 3–5 failure-mode notes

> **Definition of done:** A reproducible run inside the scaffold repo that outputs Recall@K results for ≥2 retrieval variants on N=30 tasks.

---

## 3. Research Findings

### 3.1 BM25 for Code Retrieval
- BM25 is the standard baseline retriever used in the original SWE-bench paper
- The scaffold's custom BM25-Okapi implementation (no `rank-bm25` dependency) uses an inverted index with IDF + camelCase-aware tokenization — this is solid
- SWE-bench provides pre-processed BM25 retrieval datasets (`SWE-bench_bm25_13K`, `SWE-bench_bm25_27K`) but your scaffold does its own indexing, which is more evaluable

### 3.2 Dense Retrieval
- `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` (the default) is a reasonable lightweight model, but it has a **max sequence length of 256 tokens** — the scaffold truncates files to 8000 chars (~2000 tokens), but the model internally truncates further
- For code, specialized models like `microsoft/codebert-base` or `Salesforce/codet5p-110m-embedding` would likely outperform, but `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` is fine for a Week 1 baseline
- Dense retrieval is expected to capture semantic intent better (e.g., "authentication bug" → `auth.py`) but may miss exact identifiers

### 3.3 Hybrid (BM25 + Dense via RRF)
- Already implemented with RRF (k=60), fetching 3× top_k from each method
- Research consensus (2024-2025): hybrid is the "safest default for production RAG" — combining lexical precision with semantic understanding
- **This is nearly free to add as an ablation** since the code already exists

### 3.4 Key Risk: Path Normalization
> [!CAUTION]
> The retrieval metrics in [metrics/retrieval.py](file:///Users/mertalbeyoglu/yr4/snlp/SNLP-Eval/src/harness/metrics/retrieval.py) do **exact string matching** between retrieved and gold contexts. A mismatch like `src/foo.py` vs `./src/foo.py` will **silently tank Recall@K**.

The SWE-bench adapter extracts gold files from patches using [b/](file:///Users/mertalbeyoglu/yr4/snlp/SNLP-Eval/src/harness/gatherers/rag_bm25.py#100-126) prefix stripping (line 134 of [swebench.py](file:///Users/mertalbeyoglu/yr4/snlp/SNLP-Eval/src/harness/benchmarks/swebench.py)), producing paths like `src/auth.py`. The BM25 gatherer uses `fpath.relative_to(repo_path).as_posix()` which also produces `src/auth.py`. **These should match**, but verify on Day 1.

### 3.5 SWE-bench Repo Cloning Risk
- The adapter clones repos via `git clone --depth 1` + `git fetch --depth 1 origin <commit>` + `git checkout <commit>`
- Shallow clones + specific commit fetch can fail for older/force-pushed commits
- First run on N=30 will be slow (many git clones); subsequent runs use cached repos

### 3.6 Failure Modes to Watch For
1. **Path mismatch** — retrieved vs gold file paths not normalized identically
2. **Single-file issues dominate** — most SWE-bench Lite tasks modify 1–2 files, so Recall@K can be saturated at small K
3. **Query quality** — problem statements vary in specificity; vague ones hurt all retrieval methods
4. **Large repos** — BM25 indexing is fast, but dense embedding of large repos is slow (hundreds of files × 8000 chars each)
5. **Missing file types** — the gatherers only index [.py](file:///Users/mertalbeyoglu/yr4/snlp/SNLP-Eval/src/harness/runner.py), `.java`, `.ts`, `.cs`, `.js`; SWE-bench Lite is all Python, so this is fine

